          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E7F3BEE0-1363-4EDB-A413-5989EF67FB57&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussia-kills-six-more-civilians-as-ukrainians-struggle-to-resume-routine-bca89603&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">周一，俄罗斯导弹袭击了乌克兰克里维罗市的民用建筑。照片：Arsen Dzodzaiev/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098607"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ian-lovett" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊恩·洛维特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 2:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-kills-six-more-civilians-as-ukrainians-struggle-to-resume-routine-bca89603"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰克里维里——周一早上，当泰蒂安娜·库彻听到第一声爆炸声时，她走上阳台，拍了一张约一英里外滚滚浓烟的照片——经过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">17 个月的战争</a>，她已经习惯了这种场景。</p><p>下一枚导弹击中了她的大楼，造成至少六人死亡，其中包括住在楼下的一位母亲和她 10 岁的女儿。</p><p> “一切都在震动，”55 岁的库彻说。 “盘子都掉下来了。”</p><p>战争已经过去一年多了，俄罗斯的导弹和炮弹正在吞噬在距离前线数英里的城市里进行日常事务的乌克兰人。俄罗斯称其目标是军事设施，但乌克兰中部工业区克里维罗格的袭击是过去一周发生的一系列袭击事件中的最新一起，这些袭击造成平民死亡和基础设施受损。港口城市敖德萨多次遭到俄罗斯导弹袭击，导致其大教堂以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">粮食出口的关键基础设施</a>受损。周一，南部城市赫尔松的炮击造成至少四人死亡。</p><p>乌克兰总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基在 Telegram 上写道：“敌人一直顽固地攻击城市、市中心，炮击民用物体和住房。”他补充说，克里维罗格公寓楼的五层楼已被摧毁。 “但这种恐怖不会吓到我们，也不会击垮我们。我们正在努力拯救我们的人民。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="447" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826840?width=700&amp;height=447" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，俄罗斯对乌克兰克里维罗发动袭击后，一台起重机被运来，回收人员搬运导弹碎片。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anatolii stepanov/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>导弹在公寓楼上炸开了一个 50 英尺的洞，并损坏了四分之一英里外的建筑物。据乌克兰官员称，已有 70 多人受伤。</p><p>几分钟之内，熟悉而残酷的例行公事就上演了。一台起重机被用来拆除建筑物不稳定的部分。红十字会搭建了一个帐篷，志愿者在那里包扎轻伤，而那些伤势较严重（例如脱臼）的人则被送上救护车并送往医院。心理学家随时提供服务。</p><p>数百名志愿者来到该地区，清理玻璃并分发水。</p><p>在街对面的学校，仍然完好无损的窗户被从框架上取下并带入室内，以免再次罢工时窗户破碎。</p><p>爆炸破坏了沿街的十几座建筑物。两栋大楼的屋顶上悬挂着混凝土板。穿着衬衫的商人拿着胶合板来遮盖破损的窗户。一位头上蒙着花朵图案头巾的老妇人正在扫人行道上的玻璃。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826901?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，乌克兰克里维罗市，救援队在一座被导弹击中的公寓楼废墟中开展工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Libkos/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>与此同时，袭击的受害者很快就开始尝试继续他们的日常生活。</p><p>库彻和她的丈夫站在他们大楼的街对面，排队等待为破碎的窗户取塑料罩。他们不确定什么时候才能被允许回到里面，库彻还穿着他们跑下楼梯冲出大楼时穿的粉色袜子和蓝色塑料拖鞋。</p><p>他们说，今晚他们会和她母亲住在一起，但计划在可能的时候搬回去。</p><p> “这是我们的家，”库彻的丈夫 Serhiy Kukol 说。 “一想到要离开家就很难受。”</p><p>雅娜·帕纽塔 (Yana Panyuta) 受了轻伤：爆炸将她撞到了位于公寓楼后面的家中的墙上，并短暂昏迷不醒。当她苏醒过来时，她知道了该怎么做：她找到了她的母亲和他们的狗，并把所有人都带出了该地区。几个小时后，她来到学校，登记为受害者，希望稍后能获得赔偿。她家的 14 扇窗户全部被炸碎。</p><p> 42 岁的维多利亚·卢皮伊丘克 (Viktoria Lupiychuk) 和她的母亲也在等待登记。这些妇女和卢皮丘克 12 岁的女儿在波兰度过了战争的大部分时间，但几个月前回到了克里维罗，希望能够缓解战争初期（当时俄罗斯军队正在逼近）所面临的严重威胁。在这座南方城市——现在已经结束了。</p><p> “你不认为这会发生在你身上，”她说，并补充说，当她读到其他地区的导弹袭击时，她想，“这很可怕，但你不认为导弹会击中你的建筑物。”</p><p>她的母亲泰蒂安娜·特洛齐克 (Tetiana Trotsik) 表示，她不确定他们在公寓里是否会再次感到安全。她的孙女与被杀的10岁女孩在同一个舞蹈班。她认为隔壁的乌克兰安全局大楼就是目标。该机构位于第聂伯罗的另一座建筑上周遭到袭击。</p><p>卢皮丘克说，她对此类罢工仍在继续感到愤怒。她说，西方领导人表达了对乌克兰人勇敢的钦佩，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在制止暴力方面</a>却做得不够。</p><p> “目前，我们已经搬到我亲戚家了，”卢皮丘克说。 “不幸的是，我们别无选择，只能尽可能回到这里。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——尼基塔·尼古拉延科 (Nikita Nikolaienko) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ian Lovett： <a href="mailto:ian.lovett@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ian.lovet@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 18:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-kills-six-more-civilians-as-ukrainians-struggle-to-resume-routine-bca89603</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-kills-six-more-civilians-as-ukrainians-struggle-to-resume-routine-bca89603<author><![CDATA[Ian Lovett]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Economic Recovery Weakens]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>制造业和服务业的新数据强化了反弹停滞的景象<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097544"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826451?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，一名工人在中国杭州的一家工厂加工汽车轴承。新数据表明，疫情后消费经济的提振已经消散。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097544"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">谢一凡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 1:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——7月份中国制造业和服务业活动的主要经济指标疲弱，这表明世界第二大经济体正在失去动力，尽管当局表现出扭转趋势的意愿有限。</p><p>一系列经济挑战正在拖累中国的前景，包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">青年失业</a>、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通货紧缩压力</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">房地产市场长期放缓</a>。第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国整体经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>新公布的数据表明七月份继续疲软。国家统计局周一表示，其采购经理人指数连续第四个月保持收缩，而服务业活动指标则跌至今年以来的最低水平。政府还公布了令人失望的就业、建筑和出口数据。</p><p>这些数据是 2023 年下半年的一些最新数据，这些最新数据显示，面对青年失业率高达 21% 等挑战，疫情后春季消费经济的提振是如何消散的。随着越来越多的建筑和房地产购买疲软迹象，它们提醒我们，不能指望中国能够为因持续通胀和增长担忧而担忧的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-is-still-too-confident-about-chinas-economy-2c120c5d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球经济</a>（尤其是欧洲）带来巨大好处。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826595?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周六，北京一处公寓楼建筑工地的工人们。七月份建筑活动大幅下滑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国当局似乎不愿采取重大干预措施，尽管经济疲软模式削弱了个人和企业信心，从而可能导致经济衰退进一步恶化。</p><p> 7 月初发布的旨在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">支撑私营部门</a>和改善商业信心的 31 点计划似乎对经济学家来说范围有限。他们对中国国家规划机构周一公布的新措施也很冷淡，这些措施旨在在偏远地区建设更多购物中心、促进社区重建以及推动地方政府鼓励汽车销售。</p><p>这些行动带有在债务问题出现时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-is-still-too-confident-about-chinas-economy-2c120c5d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">促进投资</a>的味道，而不是像减税或补贴这样可能将现金直接送到消费者手中并刺激更直接的消费活动的措施。</p><p> “展望未来，需要政策支持来防止中国经济陷入衰退，”伦敦凯投宏观的经济学家在一份报告中告诉客户。</p><p>周一公布的主要数据点是中国官方制造业采购经理人指数，7 月从 6 月的 49 微升至 49.3，但仍低于区分扩张与收缩的 50 大关。该数字略好于《华尔街日报》调查的经济学家预期的 49。</p><p>与美国在新冠疫情后的表现形成鲜明对比的是，中国经济疲软给国内外带来了风险。随着通货紧缩压力变得更加明显，这一点尤其正确。</p><p>由于企业业绩疲弱引发竞争和降价，价格下跌将进一步拉低中国经济，因为企业会亏损、客户推迟订单并裁员。虽然来自中国的更便宜的产品将吸引世界各地的消费者，但通货紧缩也意味着这个大国对国外生产的商品的购买力下降。</p><p>中国官员和一些经济学家否认经济正处于通缩边缘的观点。毕竟，北京仍预计 2023 年国内生产总值 (GDP) 增长 5%，这将超过大多数主要国家的增长率——其中一些国家可能面临衰退。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=36C897CD-0391-4CD6-A2F4-AAB54C8FB90E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国在20世纪50年代发明了太阳能电池板。但在全球技术市场上占据主导地位的却是中国。 《华尔街日报》审视了该行业的权力动态，以及美国是否能够重新夺回其先锋地位。图片插图：Amogh Alva Vaz<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，中国一连串令人失望的经济统计数据，以及人们对从房价到就业前景等各方面的信心减弱的迹象，都向其他经济学家表明，在经历了数十年的持续扩张之后，中国可能会面临与包括日本在内的其他经济体一样的清算。 20世纪90年代。</p><p>近年来，债务在很大程度上推动了中国的经济增长，因为经济主要是投资拉动型的，政府修建了桥梁、铁路、住房和其他有形工程。当局未能实施被认为是产生消费者力量所必需的政策，从而使 18 万亿美元的经济体的扩张走上更健康的轨道。</p><p>作为中国每月公布的经济初步指标，PMI 被认为是领先指标。</p><p> PMI分项指数显示，就业连续第五个月萎缩，服务业商业活动数据创去年12月以来的最低水平，当时北京取消了三年来限制旅游公司和餐馆<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-scraps-most-testing-quarantine-requirements-in-covid-19-policy-pivot-11670398522?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的严厉新冠封锁措施</a>。 7 月份建筑业分类指数从上个月的 55.7 降至 51.2，为 2020 年 2 月以来的最低数字。</p><p>凯投宏观预测，全球对中国制造商品的需求将进一步降温，并削弱中国的出口。周一的数据凸显了这一风险，尽管新订单总量略有改善，但新出口订单 PMI 分类指数跌至六个月低点。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826597?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">位于中国东部山东省的一家机械设备制造厂。 7月份中国官方制造业PMI仍低于扩张与收缩的分界线。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> ING 经济学家罗伯特·卡内尔 (Robert Carnell) 预计，7 月份同样疲软的非制造业 PMI 再次大幅下滑，可能会将其推向紧缩区域，从而抵消制造业的任何改善。</p><p>经济学家表示，中国领导层正在释放更多政策支持的信号，尽管行动是零敲碎打的。卡内尔表示：“到目前为止，这还没有转化为市场许多人已经习惯期待的那种大规模财政政策刺激措施。” “我们认为它不会到来。”</p><p>凯投宏观经济学家指出：“除非尽快推出具体支持，否则近期需求下滑的风险可能会自我强化。”</p><p>中国最高决策机构政治局上周承认，住房政策需要调整，许多城市取消了房地产繁荣时期实施的购房限制。私营数据公司中国房地产信息公司周一表示，7月份全国100家最大开发商销售私人住房价值490亿美元，比6月份减少三分之一，为三年来最低月度销售额。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Xiao Xiao、Grace Zhu 和曹丽对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给谢一凡<a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 17:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2<author><![CDATA[Stella Yifan Xie]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>经济预测/预测</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>经济预测</category><category>预测</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Niger Coup Leaders Detain Ministers, Party Officials]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>逮捕可能会使非洲和西方领导人解决反恐盟友危机的外交变得复杂<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098397"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826728?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔首都尼亚美，警察在支持政变策划者的游行外围。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Djibo Issifou/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098397"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：伯努瓦<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">·福孔 (Benoit Faucon)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-hinshaw" itemprop="url" rel="author">德鲁·欣肖 (Drew Hinshaw)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日中午 12:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔政变领导人周一逮捕了被拘留的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆所在政党的几名部长和高级成员，这对非洲国家<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-general-declares-himself-leader-as-russian-mercenary-hails-coup-d47efa68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为这场危机寻求外交解决方案的努力造成了打击，这场危机已经动摇了</a>美国的主要反恐盟友之一。</p><p>知情人士称，被捕者包括石油部长马哈马内·萨尼·马哈马杜（巴祖姆前任马哈马杜·伊素福的儿子）、矿业部长乌塞尼·哈迪扎图以及尼日尔民主与社会主义党执行委员会主席富马科耶·加多。 。</p><p>知情人士称，该国内政部长、国防部长和交通部长上周被捕。</p><p> “逮捕的目的是斩首[NPDS]，以避免组织大规模抗议活动，”巴祖姆政党的一名高级成员说。 “他们还想在军事干预时将他们用作人质。”</p><p>这些逮捕行动必然会使非洲领导人在美国和尼日尔前殖民国家法国的支持下促使尼日尔军政府释放巴祖姆并恢复总统职位的努力变得更加复杂。伊素福在 2021 年巴祖姆当选之前一直担任尼日尔总统，目前仍然是尼日尔政坛的重要人物，他被视为此类努力的核心对话者。</p><p>在周日举行的紧急峰会上，西非国家经济共同体领导人表示，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将给由总统卫队队长奥马尔·查尼将军领导的尼日尔军政府</a>一周的时间做出让步。如果做不到这一点，该组织（西非经共体）的领导人表示，他们将采取更有力的措施，包括可能的军事干预，以使巴祖姆重新掌权。</p><p>西非领导人还宣布了一系列痛苦的金融和贸易制裁，包括暂停向尼日尔出售电力和燃料，并冻结该国在地区央行的储备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。欧盟还暂停了与尼日尔的安全合作和财政支持。照片：达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>周六，欧盟和法国表示，他们已暂停对尼日尔政府每年数亿美元的财政支持，而美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯警告说，美国对该国的援助面临危险。</p><p>法国官员周一表示，他们希望共同的经济和政治压力能够说服尼日尔武装部队放弃支持尼日尔总统卫队及其领导人奇亚尼领导的叛乱。</p><p>尼日尔拥有一个军事领导的政府，对尼日利亚等强大的西非国家以及美国和欧洲构成了巨大风险，尼日利亚与尼日尔有着约 1,000 英里的边界。三人都与巴祖姆政府和尼日尔军方密切合作，打击撒哈拉以南半干旱地带萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>欧盟还依靠尼日尔阻止西非移民进入利比亚并从那里进入欧洲。</p><p>美国和欧洲官员担心军政府可能会寻求与莫斯科建立密切关系，就像尼日尔的几个邻国，包括马里和布基纳法索，在政变废黜民选总统后所做的那样。</p><p>克里姆林宫发言人</p>德米特里·佩斯科夫周一呼吁“迅速恢复该国法治，并要求各方保持克制，以免造成人员伤亡。”<p></p><p>近年来，美国花费了 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，该国拥有美国无人机和美国突击队，他们训练了尼日尔特种部队，并在打击基地组织和伊斯兰国当地分支机构的战斗任务中为他们提供建议。目前约有1100名美军驻扎在尼日尔。</p><p>在一轮似乎没有立即产生成果的航天飞机外交中，穆罕默德·代比，</p>乍得过渡总统周日在尼日尔首都尼亚美会见了尼日尔军政府领导人奇亚尼和巴祖姆。<p></p><p>乍得政府表示，代比访问的目的是“不惜一切代价避免公开冲突和国家孤立”。它还警告说，如果危机持续下去，萨赫勒地区的恐怖组织将从中受益。</p><p> <em>—Noemie Bisserbe 对本文做出了贡献。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 16:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1<author><![CDATA[Benoit FauconDrew Hinshaw]]></author><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>法律诉讼 - 高管</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>法律诉讼 - 高管</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel’s Arab Citizens Sit Out Protests Against Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>许多人表示，争取犹太民主的斗争让他们感到疏远<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826600/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="来自以色列雅法的律师阿贝德·卡布布 (Abed Kaboub) 表示，阿拉伯公民不觉得自己是以色列国家的一部分。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>来自以色列雅法的律师阿贝德·卡布布表示，阿拉伯公民不觉得自己是以色列国家的一部分。科比·沃尔夫 (Kobi Wolf) 为《华尔街日报》<span>撰稿 科比·沃尔夫 (Kobi Wolf) 为《华尔街日报》撰稿</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097985"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097985"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：多夫<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">·利伯 (Dov Lieber)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">阿里·弗兰兹莱奇 (Ari Flanzraich)</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日中午 12:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>特拉维夫——几个月来，数十万以色列人走上街头，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡限制该国最高法院权力的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">分裂计划</a>。一些人称这是一场为犹太国家灵魂而战的斗争，他们用几乎宇宙论的术语来形容这场战斗，因为他们为维护他们所说的反对未来独裁政府的唯一障碍而奋斗。</p><p>该国 200 万阿拉伯公民（占总人口的五分之一以上）基本上被排除在外。</p><p>乍一看，他们的缺席很奇怪。最高法院一直是阿拉伯公民权利最强有力的捍卫者之一。法律专家表示，政府限制法院权力并将更多控制权交给民选官员的计划可能会为旨在剥夺阿拉伯公民权利的立法铺平道路，从而对以色列少数民族造成最大伤害。</p><p>不过，以色列的阿拉伯人表示，他们长期以来一直感到与国家疏远，并且关于犹太人民未来的辩论与他们的日常问题（例如犯罪和失业）没有太大关系。许多人说他们已经感觉自己像二等公民。</p><p> “阿拉伯人不参与，因为他们不觉得自己是国家的一部分，而更像是一个附属物，”来自阿拉伯裔犹太人混居城市雅法的 41 岁律师阿贝德·卡布布 (Abed Kaboub) 说。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡政府表示，需要进行彻底改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，以重新调整司法系统</a>，该系统攫取了太多权力，且过于左倾。抗议者经常谈论所有人平等，包括该国的阿拉伯人口。但他们也严重利用犹太复国主义理想，将以色列描绘成犹太人的家园。抗议活动中到处都是以色列国旗，歌声中还唱着代表犹太灵魂的国歌“Hatikva”。</p><p>阿拉伯公民表示，这样的形象可能会让以色列的非犹太人感到反感。许多人认为，示威者的民主口号听起来很空洞，因为它们没有解决以色列对西岸的占领问题，那里有两百万巴勒斯坦人生活在以色列军事统治和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-palestinians-battle-israeli-troops-and-the-palestinian-authority-deepening-unrest-11663761718?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">摇摇欲坠的巴勒斯坦权力机构的</a>混合之下。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826649?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿拉伯与犹太混居城市雅法的一座清真寺。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的科比·沃尔夫</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826613?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">七月份，在特拉维夫举行的反对以色列政府司法改革计划的抗议活动中，以色列国旗随处可见。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kobi Wolf/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“把自己放在他们的位置上。聚集在以色列国旗周围并唱[国歌]不是他们会支持的事情，”居住在犹太阿拉伯城市海法的巴勒斯坦律师戴安娜·布图说。</p><p>特拉维夫和其他城市每周举行的示威活动已<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">连续举行 30 周</a>，吸引了一小群挥舞巴勒斯坦旗帜的反占领抗议者。</p><p>全国抗议运动是全国各地示威团体的伞式组织，该组织表示，一些阿拉伯以色列人参加了海法的抗议活动，但也承认“合理的担忧可能阻止其他人加入”。</p><p>该组织表示：“通过认识到不同社区面临的独特挑战并重视不同的观点，我们努力建立信任和团结的桥梁。”</p><p>以色列一些阿拉伯公民长期奉行抵制政治进程的政策，这是对犹太国家理念反感的一部分。从历史上看，阿拉伯公民在全国选举中的投票率远低于犹太以色列人。</p><p>其他阿拉伯公民表示，抗议活动没有解决他们的具体问题，包括阿拉伯城镇的高贫困率和犯罪率。</p><p>对于许多阿拉伯以色列人来说，比如来自阿拉伯以色列城市乌姆法姆的 30 岁希伯来语教师艾哈迈德·马哈米德 (Ahmad Mahamid)，维护以色列自由民主的问题与他的社区面临的日常斗争无关。</p><p>根据以色列中央统计局的数据，与犹太以色列人相比，阿拉伯以色列人可能更贫穷，预期寿命更短，对生活的满意度也更低。他们长期以来一直抱怨政府资源分配方面的歧视导致他们的学校条件较差，缺乏住房和适当的基础设施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="905" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826630?width=1260&amp;height=905" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2021 年 3 月，在阿拉伯以色列城市乌姆法赫姆，阿拉伯抗议者站在一个竞选广告牌后面，广告牌上画着以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ariel Schalit/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826628?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议员艾曼·奥德（中间穿着衬衫和西装外套）参加了反对内塔尼亚胡司法改革的抗议活动，并呼吁阿拉伯公民参与其中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tsafrir Abayov/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>阿拉伯城镇也遭受着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-palestinians-caught-in-escalating-cycle-of-violence-in-jerusalem-and-west-bank-11675001861?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">日益恶化的暴力事件</a>之苦。根据处理阿拉伯与犹太人关系的非营利组织亚伯拉罕倡议 (Abraham Initiatives) 的数据，今年有 111 名以色列阿拉伯公民在犯罪相关事件中丧生，比 2022 年同期增加了 135%。</p><p>马哈米德说：“他们忙于捍卫他们私人的小民主，而我们则忙于生存，避免任何可能随机击中我们的流弹。”</p><p>以色列最高法院过去曾废除旨在限制巴勒斯坦人和阿拉伯公民权利的法律。例如，法院在 2000 年具有里程碑意义的案件中表示，建立在国有土地上的犹太社区不能禁止阿拉伯人迁入。法院还废除了对任何呼吁抵制以色列的人实施制裁的立法，以及阻止巴勒斯坦人索赔损失的法律来自被占领西岸的以色列安全部队。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡的联盟由右翼、极端民族主义和宗教保守派政党组成，已讨论通过立法，通过禁止任何不承认以色列为犹太国家的政党进入议会（以色列议会），从而有效限制阿拉伯人的政治参与。今天的最高法院可能会否决此类立法，而司法改革可能会限制法院这样做的能力。</p><p>左翼阿拉伯犹太哈达什党领袖艾曼·奥德参加了一些抗议活动，并呼吁阿拉伯公民参与其中。</p><p> “阿拉伯社会必须加强对抗议活动的参与，”奥德本月早些时候在推特上写道。他写道：“尽管有合理的批评和挑战，但我们将成为第一个因进一步限制民主空间而受到伤害的人。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，为阿拉伯公民争取平等权利的团体表示，他们已经输掉了向法院提起的大部分案件。其中包括一项法律，在维护共同的共同价值观的基础上，有效地允许阿拉伯人口众多地区的小型犹太社区禁止阿拉伯人迁入。法院维持了另一项严格限制约旦河西岸阿拉伯以色列人和巴勒斯坦人婚姻的法律。最大的打击发生在 2018 年，当时法院在一项将以色列定义为犹太国家的法律上站在政府一边。</p><p>特拉维夫国家安全研究所的民意调查显示，阿拉伯以色列人对最高法院的信心近年来不断下降，从 2017 年的 75% 降至 2022 年的 42%。</p><p>但许多阿拉伯裔以色列人对这一波反政府抗议活动最大的抱怨是，示威者对约旦河西岸缺乏关注。自以色列 1967 年从约旦手中夺取领土以来，那里的巴勒斯坦人一直生活在以色列的军事占领之下。</p><p> “无论他们试图做什么，都不会改变以色列占领的事实，他们只是忽视这一事实，”来自阿拉伯以色列城镇塔伊贝的 29 岁教师哈桑·哈吉-叶海亚 (Hasan Haj-Yahya) 说。 “为什么我们要浪费日日夜夜去争取最终会巩固我们明知是虚假的国家形象的东西呢？” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826640?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名巴勒斯坦妇女走在被占领的约旦河西岸杰宁难民营受损的道路上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Majdi Mohammed/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 16:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Local Malls, Stuck in ‘Death Spiral,’ Plunge in Value]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>康涅狄格州水晶广场 (Crystal Mall) 2012 年价值 1.5 亿美元，最近以 950 万美元售出<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823519/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="康涅狄格州沃特福德市水晶购物中心的降价显示了近年来美国地区购物中心的命运下降的速度有多快。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>康涅狄格州沃特福德市水晶购物中心的降价显示了近年来美国地区购物中心的命运下降得有多快。约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻<span>约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kate-king" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯特·金</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>康涅狄格州沃特福德——水晶购物中心的停车场过去非常拥挤，家长们会在其中一个入口附近排队送孩子下车，而不是寻找停车位。</p><p>现在，康涅狄格州海岸这座 20 世纪 80 年代的区域购物中心周围大片开裂的人行道上杂草比汽车还多。 2012 年，评估师对水晶广场的估价为 1.53 亿美元，6 月份的一次止赎拍卖中，水晶广场以略高于 950 万美元的价格售出。</p><p> “现在看来，这令人沮丧，”沃特福德的最高民选领导人、第一任议员罗布·布鲁尔(Rob Brule)说。他在这个工人阶级小镇长大，并将这座购物中心描述为他年轻时的社交中心。</p><p>水晶广场的降价显示，近年来，由于购物习惯的改变、来自其他零售业的竞争以及网上购物的兴起， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shopping-mall-nostalgia-auction-420a44f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国地区购物中心的价值</a>迅速恶化。</p><p>房地产研究公司 Green 的美国零售和工业研究主管文斯·蒂博恩 (Vince Tibone) 表示，较旧的低端购物中心的价值至少比 2016 年底购物中心估值达到顶峰时低 50%，在某些情况下还低 70% 以上。街道。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">穆迪</a>分析公司称，现在，随着这些物业支持的超过 140 亿美元的贷款将在未来 12 个月内到期，陷入困境的购物中心正在拖欠债务。随着抵押贷款利率大幅上升，债务再融资将更具挑战性且成本更高。</p><p>穆迪商业房地产经济分析主管凯文·费根(Kevin Fagan)表示，通过商业抵押贷款支持证券融资的购物中心中，约有五分之一处于水下状态，这意味着这些房产的价值低于它们所支持的贷款。</p><p>在某些情况下，它们的价值要低得多。晶城广场的前所有者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPG" class="">西蒙地产集团 (Simon Property Group)</a><span class="company-name-type">在</span>疫情期间停止支付 8100 万美元的未偿 CMBS 债务，并于去年归还了其自 1999 年以来拥有的房产的钥匙。</p><p>穆迪表示，这笔贷款被纳入由著名投资者卡尔·伊坎做空的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carl-icahn-placing-a-big-bet-against-mall-owners-11574201244?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">CMBX 6 指数</a>中，预计清算时将损失 7000 万美元，约占未偿余额的 87%。</p><p>类似的故事正在全国各地上演。 Trepp 表示，在印第安纳州，Muncie Mall 提供了 3100 万美元的贷款，但经过 3 月份的评估后，其价值仅为 600 万美元。这家拥有 52 年历史的购物中心九年前估价为 7300 万美元，直到 2018 年才几乎客满。</p><p>特雷普表示，位于新泽西州中部的伍德布里奇中心 (Woodbridge Center) 是一家占地 110 万平方英尺的购物中心，今年早些时候的估值为 8600 万美元，比 2014 年疫情前的上次估值下降了 76%。该购物中心的两笔 CMBS 贷款被取消抵押品赎回权，未偿余额总计近 2.5 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826219?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “We&#39;ve seen dozens and dozens of malls liquidated at losses or had their values cut,” said Manus Clancy, senior managing director at Trepp.</p><p> Not all malls are on the brink of disaster.较新、位置优越的房产和强大的租户名单正在为投资者带来健康的人流量和回报。 But even these high-quality malls have declined in value by an estimated 50% since 2016, Tibone said, making malls one of the worst performing commercial real-estate sectors over that period.</p><p> Widespread <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-chains-shed-stores-but-it-isnt-good-for-business-11605436204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">department-store closures</a> beginning in 2018 hastened malls&#39; decline. Large mall anchors like</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/M" class="">Macy&#39;s</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Bon-Ton, JCPenney and Sears closed about 875 department stores between 2018 and the end of 2020, according to Green Street, compared with a combined 175 in 2016 and 2017.<p></p><p> “It really accelerated the death spiral of the industry,” Tibone said. “你开始失去百货商店，这导致中心的销售额和客流量下降。然后更多的租户离开。 It starts this awful cycle.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flocal-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The death spiral at the Crystal Mall started in 2018, when anchor tenant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sears-exit-would-leave-big-holes-in-malls-some-landlords-welcome-that-1539342000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Sears declared bankruptcy</a> and announced plans to close.三年后，梅西百货关闭了门店。 Overall revenue at Crystal Mall declined 39% between 2018 and 2022, while expenses fell only 10%, according to Trepp.</p><p> “All the stores used to be open, and everything used to be nice and beautiful,” said Melissa Rodriguez, 40 years old, standing outside the mall&#39;s food court one recent afternoon.</p><p> Now, many of the shops have closed. One of her favorite stores, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBBYQ" class="">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> is shutting its location after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-investors-arent-giving-up-on-bed-bath-beyond-7c1dcd37?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">declaring bankruptcy</a> earlier this year. Before the pandemic, Rodriguez said, she often visited the mall twice a week but now comes only once a month.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like before,” she said.</p><p> Christmas Tree Shops, which shared an anchor space with Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/christmas-tree-shops-to-liquidate-all-stores-ea53da39?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">also closing following bankruptcy</a> . Once those retailers vacate, JCPenney will be the only anchor tenant left at Crystal Mall. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823825?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Crystal Mall fell into decline following closings of two anchor stores, Sears and Macy&#39;s, in recent years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Brule, Waterford&#39;s first selectman, said he would like to see the property redeveloped into a mixed-use site.他设想为参观神秘岛附近的游客建造一座酒店，并为当地消防员、教师以及当地潜艇制造商通用动力电船公司的员工提供住房。 Maybe a hockey rink or a bowling alley, somewhere for the town&#39;s teenagers to gather.</p><p> “That&#39;s what this property could be,” Brule said.</p><p> It is unlikely these dreams for Crystal Mall will be realized under its new owner, New York-based investment firm Namdar Realty Group.布鲁尔说，一位公司高管在一次介绍性电话会议上告诉布鲁尔，公司不会重新开发房产。</p><p> Namdar Chief Executive Igal Namdar said the company plans to implement an “aggressive leasing strategy to attract a mix of national and local tenants” to Crystal Mall.</p><p> Write to Kate King at <a href="mailto:kate.king@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kate.king@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d<author><![CDATA[Kate King]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> commercial re</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Retail/Wholesale</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物中心/超市</category><category>Real Estate Services/Transactions</category><category> Retail Real Estate</category><category> Commercial/Industrial Real Estate</category><category> Real Estate/Construction</category><category>房地产</category><category>零售</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Commercial RE</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Moody&#39;s</category><category>运动控制</category><category>Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</category><category> BBBYQ</category><category> Macy&#39;s</category><category>中号</category><category>Simon Property Group</category><category> SPG</category><category> Kevin Fagan</category><category> Rob Brule</category><category> Carl Icahn</category><category> Vince Tibone</category><category> Manus Clancy</category><category> corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>混合零售</category><category>shopping malls</category><category>超市</category><category>real estate services</category><category> transactions</category><category> retail real estate</category><category>商业的</category><category>industrial real estate</category><category> real estate</category><category> construction </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Benefit of Owning Stocks Over Bonds Keeps Shrinking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Some worry the rally is unsustainable after a gauge of stocks&#39; relative value falls to two-decade low <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Analysts say the premium to own stocks over bonds can&#39;t stay this low indefinitely.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Julia Nikhinson/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-goldfarb" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sam Goldfarb</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The extra reward for holding stocks instead of bonds has fallen to its lowest level in 20 years, threatening a recent hot streak for major indexes.</p><p> One method for gauging the value of stocks is to compare their earnings yield—calculated by dividing a company&#39;s expected earnings over the next year by its stock price—to the yield on government bonds, considered the closest thing to a risk-free return. The difference, sometimes called the equity-risk premium, shows how much investors are being compensated for the additional risk of owning stocks.</p><p> And right now, that isn&#39;t much.</p><p> The gap between the earnings yield of the S&amp;P 500 and the yield on the 10-year US government bond dropped to around 1.1 percentage point last week, its narrowest since 2002. The spread to the yield on the 10-year Treasury inflation-protected security, seen by some analysts as the better benchmark because corporate earnings <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-inflation-so-sticky-it-could-be-corporate-profits-b78d90b7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tend to adjust with inflation</a> , has similarly fallen to its lowest level since 2003, at around 3.5 percentage points.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>What is your approach to stocks versus bonds? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> The risk premium first started shrinking in the second half of last year.在此期间，股市从年初的抛售中企稳，尽管债券收益率因美联储加息以应对通胀而持续攀升。 This year, the premium <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stocks-havent-looked-this-unattractive-since-2007-78fc374c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has continued to dwindle</a> for slightly different reasons: Bond yields haven&#39;t risen as much, but stocks have taken flight—lifted by investors&#39; growing optimism about the economy.</p><p> Whatever happens to change it, there is a consensus on Wall Street that the equity-risk premium can&#39;t stay this low forever.</p><p> For stock prices relative to earnings to be back to where they were at the start of the 2022 selloff “when interest rates are 2x, 3x higher than they were really doesn&#39;t add up,” said Tim Urbanowicz, head of research and investment strategy at Innovator ETFs.</p><p> Investors and analysts also tend to agree that an ultralow risk premium doesn&#39;t mean that this year&#39;s stock rally has reached its conclusion.</p><p> For one thing, they point out, risk premiums have gotten much lower before—in the dot-com bubble of the late 1990s. Back then, the gap between the S&amp;P 500&#39;s earnings yield and inflation-adjusted, or “real,” Treasury yields briefly collapsed entirely, according to some measures. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826036?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fed Chair Jerome Powell last week indicated another rate increase is possible but also signaled that rates could remain steady.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Al Drago/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Looking back at history, analysts say risk premiums revert to average over time—typically because prospects for corporate earnings dim, not because investors get frightened by valuations on their own.</p><p> “I haven&#39;t found a very strong statistical relationship between the earnings yield relative to the 10-year Treasury—whether it&#39;s real or nominal—and future returns over, say, a one- or three-year horizon,” said Brian Jacobsen, chief economist of Annex Wealth Management.</p><p> Investors have another source of hope: Risk premiums could normalize because bond yields fall rather than stock prices.</p><p> Stoking this optimism, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-25-2023/card/is-the-fed-prepping-its-final-interest-rate-hike--9HVDuRwso3GtKrz2IhkL?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">many believe that the Fed is finally done</a> raising short-term interest rates.</p><p> With inflation showing signs of cooling, interest-rate futures indicate that investors think there is only a slightly better than 30% chance that the Fed raises rates again this year, according to CME Group data. At a press conference Wednesday, Fed Chair Jerome Powell <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">left the door open to another rate increase</a> , but also indicated that the central bank could opt to leave rates steady for a while if economic data cooperated.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Yields on US Treasurys largely reflect investors&#39; expectations for short-term rates over the life of a bond. Even if the Fed has reached the end of its tightening campaign, bond yields could rise further if the central bank keeps rates at current levels for longer than investors anticipate.</p><p> Still, the consensus is that both rates and bond yields should eventually decline.</p><p> That view is embedded in current bond yields. As of Friday, the yield on the benchmark 10-year Treasury inflation-protected security was around 1.6%, according to Tradeweb. However, the five-year TIPS yield was 1.9%, implying that investors expect real short-term rates to be lower in the second half than in the first half of the next 10 years.</p><p> Meanwhile, most Fed officials estimated in June that real interest rates will eventually settle at a level no higher than 0.5%.</p><p> Jacobsen, of Annex Wealth Management, said he thinks the 10-year TIPS yield could fall to 0.75% or 1% over the next 12 to 18 months.</p><p> That would mean investors are rewarded more for owning stocks, assuming indexes don&#39;t rally much further. But it would also mean that bonds prices have climbed. Jacobsen said his team has recently recommended that clients move more money into bonds after previously tilting more heavily toward stocks.</p><p> “If you look at the hiking cycles from 1989 to the present, every time they hit the plateau for rates that was pretty bullish for bonds,” he said, “and we think we&#39;re at least close to that point.”</p><p> Write to Sam Goldfarb at <a href="mailto:sam.goldfarb@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sam.goldfarb@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203<author><![CDATA[Sam Goldfarb]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>Monetary Policy</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Equity Markets</category><category>债务/债券市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务/债券市场</category><category>国家政府债务/债券市场</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>equity markets</category><category> debt</category><category>债券市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务</category><category>国家政府债务</category><category>content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Trucking Giant Yellow Shuts Down Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The 99-year-old company with 22,000 Teamsters employees advises customers and workers of shutdown <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096116"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=BA4F5A1C-1DB7-4FCE-AF62-3AB02EA23D64&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Yellow, one of the oldest and biggest US trucking businesses, is preparing to file for bankruptcy and is in discussions to sell off all or parts of the business. Photo: Charlie Riedel/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096116"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-nassauer" itemprop="url" rel="author">莎拉·纳索尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-page" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·佩奇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 30, 2023 9:31 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Yellow, one of the oldest and biggest US trucking businesses, shut down on Sunday, wrecked by a string of mergers that left it saddled with debt and stalled by a standoff with the Teamsters union.</p><p>这家拥有 99 年历史的公司以其低廉的价格而闻名，拥有 12,000 多辆卡车，为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WMT" class="">沃尔玛</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="company-name">家得宝</a>和许多其他小型企业在全国范围内运输货物。尽管吞并了竞争对手、获得了工会让步并获得了政府救助，但黄色无法提供的是为客户提供一致的服务或为投资者带来利润。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The Nashville, Tenn., company sent out notices to customers and employees saying it was ceasing all operations at midday Sunday. The Teamsters said the company notified the union it intends to file for bankruptcy.</p><p>一次故障将危及近 30,000 个工作岗位，其中包括约 22,000 名卡车司机协会成员。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-lays-off-a-swath-of-workforce-2297e8b2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周五，在该公司停止接收客户的新货后，数百名非工会员工被解雇</a>。</p><p>对于变化无常的美国卡车运输业来说，这将是收入和就业方面最大的崩溃，尽管客户表示中断应该是有限的。最近几周，许多公司将货物转移给竞争对手，加速了 Yellow 的灭亡。竞争对手表示，上周他们的销量猛增。</p><p>一位工会发言人表示：“十多年来，卡车司机们通过在工资、养老金和工作规则方面的让步，让这家公司得以维持下去。” “黄色无法管理自己，卡车司机也不能为他们做这件事。”</p><p>自 2021 年以来，Yellow 一直在推行<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-seeks-to-steady-finances-by-streamlining-operations-11622466000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成本削减和整合计划</a>，高管们表示这将改善业务。 Yellow 的一位发言人表示，在最近的重组中，该公司并未要求工会做出让步。 “Yellow 提出向员工支付更高的工资，”她说。工会“九个月来拒绝谈判”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826339?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>关闭还将对特朗普政府在 2020 年向该公司提供 7 亿美元<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-overrode-pentagon-on-truckers-700-million-pandemic-aid-panel-says-11651064400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新冠救援贷款的</a>决定带来新的审查。美国财政部目前持有 Yellow 约 30% 的股票，这些股票已暴跌，周五收于每股 71 美分。</p><p> Chris Sultemeier 表示：“这是一个令人难以置信的悲伤情况，因为这家即将在明年庆祝其 100 周年纪念日的公司可能不会再存在了。”</p>自 2020 年起担任 Yellow 董事会成员，曾任沃尔玛物流主管。<p></p><p>在周五的一份备忘录中，卡车司机告诉工会当地人，“黄色生存的可能性越来越渺茫。”工会敦促会员将工具和个人物品带回家，这样物品就不会在申请破产后被锁在门后。</p><h3>小开始</h3><p>Yellow 于 1924 年在俄克拉荷马城成立，最初是一家小型出租车和巴士公司。黄色出租车运输公司用黄色福特 T 型车和公共汽车运送当地人，最终在城市之间运送乘客。</p><p> It became a national force only after it filed for bankruptcy in 1951 and George Powell, a Kansas City, Mo., banker, bought the struggling business.他将其打造为一家受益于州际公路系统建设的长途运营商。</p><p>通过收购，它建立了一个从东海岸到西海岸的网络，帮助该承运人度过了 1980 年州际卡车运输放松管制后的几年的动荡时期，当时许多大型承运人倒闭了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825986?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">自 2009 年以来，Yellow 大部分时间都处于亏损状态，但利润从未超过 2500 万美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥林·瓦格纳/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>黄色为沃尔玛等客户提供了服务，并最终</p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>——全国运输，费率通常低于竞争对手。这些大型零售商主要将整车货物运送到商店和仓库，但 Yellow 和其他零担运输公司为客户提供了以较小数量填补库存缺口的机会。<p></p><p> 2003 年，Yellow 以约 10 亿美元的现金和股票<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB105766973940541900?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">收购了另一家零担货运公司 Roadway</a> 。两家公司都加入了工会，而许多其他零担运输竞争对手则没有。</p><p>比尔·佐拉尔斯 (Bill Zollars) 表示，这两家公司“一百年来一直试图互相残杀”。</p>他于 1999 年至 2011 年间担任 Yellow 的首席执行官。高管们相信，合并将使双方都有机会与非工会竞争对手更具竞争力。<p></p><h3>合并错误</h3><p>两家公司合并了后台功能，但没有合并网络，限制了成本节约。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB110956132986765654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2005 年，Yellow 以 13.7 亿美元收购了另一家大型竞争对手</a>USF，再次合并了后台职能，但没有合并更广泛的公司。</p><p>佐拉斯表示，当时两家公司的运营能力已接近满负荷，因此合并规模更大的业务没有意义。他说，随后 2008 年经济衰退袭来，货运需求蒸发，高管们希望他们能够更快地整合。他表示，2008 年至 2010 年间，与当时最大客户沃尔玛的业务下降了约 50%。</p><p> “如果我们知道经济衰退的持续时间和深度，我们就会更快地融入，”他说。 “事后看来是20/20。”该公司整合了 Yellow 和 Roadway 网络的某些部分，但没有整合 USF，后者是一个区域运营商网络。</p><p>高管们与卡车司机和债权人进行谈判，以避免破产并抵御投资者。 2010年，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704350304574638750418217422?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">达成了一项协议</a>，在很大程度上消灭了股东，并要求工会同意削减福利和工资。</p><p>合并及合并产生的债务<strong>&nbsp;</strong>运营不同品牌的运营复杂性继续困扰着该公司。该公司表示，2014年和2020年再次面临破产威胁。</p><p>佐拉尔斯表示，合并后公司的财务状况立即得到改善，收购为公司节省了大量成本，但事实证明经济衰退造成的损失太深了。 “我认为说债务负担是原因是不公平的，”他说。他说，目前该公司大约一半的债务来自最近的政府贷款。</p><h3>陷入中立</h3><p>自 2009 年以来，Yellow 的年收入一直徘徊在接近 50 亿美元的水平，但该公司大多数年份都处于亏损状态，利润从未超过 2500 万美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826216?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 2011 年至 2018 年担任首席执行官的詹姆斯·韦尔奇 (James Welch) 表示，他的目标是将公司作为独立的企业来运营，以避免激怒工人和工会，并取悦以不同方式使用每项服务的客户。 “在我任职期间，有人多次建议整合，我说，‘不要这样做，’”他说。</p><p>韦尔奇表示，该公司的交易债务是其失败的原因。韦尔奇表示：“我们只是承担了太多债务，而且支付过高。”韦尔奇早些时候在公司任职后，于 2011 年被贷方召回。这位前首席执行官表示，消化债务“20年来一直是一个艰难的过程”。</p><p>他说，回想起来，他希望自己能进一步缩减黄色和公路部分的业务，而偏向南佛罗里达州地区航空公司，因为它们已经成为公司生产力更高的一方。</p><p>为托运人提供咨询服务的 SJ Consulting 总裁萨蒂什·金德尔 (Satish Jindel) 表示，Yellow 的准时表现落后于竞争对手，2022 年每批货物的平均收入为 319 美元，而许多竞争对手每批货物的收入超过 400 美元。 “他们经营和管理得不好，”金德尔说。 “你必须有适当的服务才能获得优惠的价格。”</p><p> Yellow 发言人表示，债务负担、过去整合业务的失败以及之前工会的让步“都是在现任董事会或管理层就位之前很久就采取的行动的结果”。她表示，公司目前的整合计划将纠正这些错误，提高公司的竞争力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="456" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825984?width=700&amp;height=456" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Yellow is preparing to file for bankruptcy and is in talks to sell off all or parts of the business.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>新冠救援</h3><p>2020 年，当 Covid-19 大流行导致工厂和商店关闭时，该公司（当时名为 YRC Worldwide）表示，将难以偿还债务。</p><p>作为新冠疫情救助计划的一部分，联邦政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yrc-lenders-agree-to-extend-truckers-debt-terms-11594238914?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=3&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向其提供了</a>7 亿美元的贷款，为该公司提供了救命稻草，这促使贷方给予该公司三年的缓期还款期限。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-treasury-to-loan-700-million-to-trucking-firm-yrc-worldwide-11593602409?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">财政部表示</a>，黄为国防部提供的服务对国家安全非常重要。</p><p> “这是新的一天。时任 YRC 首席财务官杰米·皮尔森 (Jamie Pierson) 在 2020 年接受采访时表示：“我们不能把它搞砸了。”2021 年，在现任首席执行官达伦·霍金斯 (Darren Hawkins) 的领导下，该公司表示将利用这笔贷款来推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-seeks-to-steady-finances-by-streamlining-operations-11622466000" target="_blank" class="icon none">全面整合。</a></p><p> 2023 年 6 月的一份<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/treasury-shouldnt-have-given-pandemic-aid-to-trucking-company-report-finds-889cd7ad" target="_blank" class="icon none">国会报告</a>得出的结论是，财政部在发放贷款时规避了自己的规则，特朗普政府在向陷入困境的公司借钱时犯了错误。这笔贷款当时得到了卡车司机协会的支持，作为一项挽救就业的措施。</p><h3>卡车司机的紧张局势</h3><p>由于整个货运行业的运输需求下降导致货运量减少并导致运价下降，Yellow 今年的财务困境加剧。其现金持有量从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-is-losing-customers-as-teamsters-strike-looms-2c47bcdc" target="_blank" class="icon none">12 月的 2.35 亿美元降至 6 月的 1 亿美元左右</a>。</p><p>公司在西部地区的整合取得了进展，随后又向全国推进。这些行为引发了卡车司机和公司之间激烈且不断升级的交流。</p><p>卡车司机协会表示，该公司需要重新谈判其多年期合同（该合同将于 2024 年 3 月后到期），以实施运营变革。 Yellow 于 6 月 27 日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-is-suing-teamsters-union-over-changes-to-operations-d25b4640?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提起诉讼</a>，指控卡车司机协会阻止这些变化，并使卡车司机业务蒙受损失。该公司表示，不采取行动可能会导致 Yellow 陷入清算。</p><p> 6 月份，该公司寻求推迟两项养老基金付款，导致其缴款拖欠 5000 万美元。卡车司机工会威胁说，如果公司不付款，他们将在七月中旬罢工，这吓坏了顾客。</p><p>帮助零售商和制造商管理货运的 TranzAct Technologies 高管迈克·里根 (Mike Regan) 表示，这场冲突引发了最新的金融混乱。 “卡车司机显然夸大了他们的手，”他说。</p><p>卡车司机协会主席肖恩·奥布莱恩表示，黄色问题的根源是管理不善，而不是工会的要求。</p><p> “我们不希望看到任何公司遭受损失并倒闭，但在某些时候，我们不能继续牺牲工资，以及我们的祖先和前辈在我们的货运部门长期艰苦奋斗的条件，”他在会上表示。 7月22日在亚特兰大举行的集会。</p><p> Yellow <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-wins-reprieve-from-lenders-including-u-s-government-8f8553b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">获得了 30 天的缓刑，</a>以补足养老金和福利基金的支付。但等待的顾客却寥寥无几。</p><p>新泽西州货运经纪公司 Tucker Company Worldwide 的首席执行官杰夫·塔克 (Jeff Tucker) 表示：“在这样的时期，当企业面临压力时，你只能远离。” “你让你的货物远离他们的网络。”</p><p>写信给 Sarah Nassauer <a href="mailto:Sarah.Nassauer@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(Sarah.Nassauer@wsj.com)</a>和 Paul Page ( <a href="mailto:paul.page@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paul.page@wsj.com)</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Yellow 拥有约 22,000 名卡车司机员工。本文的早期版本错误地称其雇用了 22,000 名卡车司机。 （7月29日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 01:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662<author><![CDATA[Sarah NassauerPaul Page]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category>专有的</category><category>印刷/出版</category><category>数据库/目录发布</category><category>Retail/Wholesale</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物中心/超市</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>出版</category><category>零售</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>营销</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Customer Relationship Management</category><category> Markets/Marketing</category><category> Political/General News</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>家得宝</category><category>高清</category><category>Yellow</category><category>叫喊</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>营销</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category> customer relationship management</category><category> markets</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category>印刷</category><category>出版</category><category>数据库</category><category>目录出版</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>混合零售</category><category>shopping malls</category><category>超市</category><category>media</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[While Everyone Else Fights Inflation, China’s Deflation Fears Deepen]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Some economists see parallels between China and Japan, where growth stagnated and prices fell for years <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826191/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="几个月来，生产从钢铁、水泥到化学品等产品的中国工厂的价格一直在下降。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Prices charged by Chinese factories that make products from steel to cement to chemicals have been falling for months. Cfoto/DDP/ZUMA PRESS <span>Cfoto/DDP/ZUMA PRESS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093089"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093089"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jason Douglas</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stella Yifan Xie</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 30, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Signs of deflation are becoming more prevalent across China, heaping extra pressure on Beijing to reignite growth or risk falling into an economic trap it could find hard to escape.</p><p> While the rest of the world <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">tussles with inflation</a> , China is at risk of experiencing a prolonged spell of falling prices that—if it takes root—could eat into corporate profits, sap consumer spending and push more people out of work. Its effects would ripple across the globe, easing prices for some products that countries like the US buy from China, but would also deprive the world of important Chinese demand for raw materials and consumer goods, while also creating other problems.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Prices charged by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chinese factories</a> that make products ranging from steel to cement to chemicals have been falling for months. Consumer prices, meanwhile, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deflation-looms-in-china-as-rebound-continues-to-lose-steam-b0d66d7e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">have gone flat,</a> with prices for certain goods—including sugar, eggs, clothes and household appliances—now falling on a month-over-month basis amid weak demand.</p><p> Most economists think China will probably avoid a deep and lasting period of deflation. Its economy is growing, albeit sluggishly, and the government has unveiled a variety of small stimulus measures that could help more. Earlier in July, Liu Guoqiang, a Chinese central bank official, dismissed concerns that China is slipping toward deflation.</p><p> But some economists see alarming parallels between China&#39;s current predicament and the experience of Japan, which struggled for years with deflation and stagnant growth.</p><p> In the 1990s, a collapse in stock markets and real-estate values in Japan pushed companies and households to drastically cut back spending to service burdensome debts—a so-called balance-sheet recession that some see taking shape in China today. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824718?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824719?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Data released Thursday showed industrial profits are sinking and average new home sale prices fell in June.</p><p> If China were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-is-still-too-confident-about-chinas-economy-2c120c5d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to tip into protracted deflation</a> , it has another big problem: Traditional methods of fighting it are either unpopular in Beijing, or lack potency due to the country&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fueled-by-long-credit-binge-chinas-economy-faces-drag-from-debt-purge-e4621859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">heavy debt load</a> and other issues. Beijing is wary of large deficit-financed spending programs that could juice growth and push prices higher, while big debts mean consumers and businesses are reluctant to borrow and spend.</p><p> “The big concern is whether the policy tools that they have will have much traction in terms of trying to avert deflation, or deal with deflationary pressures once they arrive,” said Eswar Prasad,</p> a professor of trade policy and economics at Cornell University and a former head of the International Monetary Fund&#39;s China division.<p></p><p> For the global economy, extended deflation in China might help cool inflation elsewhere, including the US, since its factories make up such a large share of the world&#39;s goods.</p><p> However, a flood of cut-price Chinese exports on global markets could squeeze out rival exporters in some countries, hurting jobs and investment in those economies. Chinese export prices for steel and chemicals fell by about a third over the 12 months through June.</p><p> A deflationary spell in China would also likely mean weaker Chinese demand for food, energy and raw materials, which big chunks of the world rely on for export earnings.</p><p> “The market is underestimating the deflationary impact on the global economy,” said</p> Frederic Neumann, chief Asia economist at HSBC in Hong Kong.<p></p><p> Consumer prices in the US <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">rose 3% in June</a> from a year earlier, a sharp slowdown from the 8% annual rate a year earlier but still above the 2% rate targeted by the Federal Reserve. Annual inflation in the European Union last month was 6.4% as the region continues to feel the squeeze from high energy and food prices.</p><p> In China, annual consumer-price inflation in June was zero. Producer prices fell in China last month by 5.4% from a year earlier.</p><p> Subdued consumer spending is one big reason. Some idiosyncratic factors are also at play, including a steep rise last year in the price of pork—a staple in the Chinese diet—that hasn&#39;t been repeated.</p><p> But weak price pressures are also a payback of sorts for China&#39;s experience during the Covid-19 pandemic, when exports rocketed thanks to Western demand for gym equipment, home improvement supplies and other goods.</p><p> The demand surge helped push Chinese producer prices up 12% between the start of 2020 and their peak in April last year, according to an index calculated by Moody&#39;s Analytics. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826204?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> With global energy and food prices weaker than before, economists expect overall consumer prices in China to stay nearly flat, or even fall.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When governments lifted lockdowns and Western demand eased, the trend reversed. Producer prices began falling on a year-over-year basis in October and have kept falling every month since.</p><p> Chinese factories, which expanded to meet Western demand during the pandemic, now face overcapacity. The hope was that Chinese consumers would step into the breach and soak up excess inventories as export markets dried up. But that hasn&#39;t happened, and as more businesses pivot toward selling into the domestic market, the downward pressure on prices is building.</p><p> With global energy and food prices also weaker than before, economists expect overall consumer prices in China to stay nearly flat, or even fall, in the coming months. In addition to many foodstuffs and clothing items, prices have also been falling for electric vehicles, as Chinese automakers and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">Tesla</a> have slashed prices amid slower sales growth and in an effort to win more share in a crowded market.</p><p> China could escape further deflation if growth regains momentum later this year, helped by government stimulus, as some economists anticipate. Nomura economists expect annual consumer-price inflation in China of negative 0.2% in the third quarter, with inflation eventually turning positive again toward the end of the year. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=36C897CD-0391-4CD6-A2F4-AAB54C8FB90E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhile-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The US invented solar panels in the 1950s. But it&#39;s China that&#39;s grown to dominate the technology in global markets. The WSJ examines the power dynamics in the industry, and whether the US can reclaim its pioneering role. Photo illustration: Amogh Alva Vaz<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The risk for China is that deflation proves more persistent than expected. Falling prices tend to squeeze spending as consumers await a better deal tomorrow, reinforcing a downward spiral.</p><p> The longer it lasts, the more severe its effects become. Entrenched deflation means debts become harder to bear as profits and incomes fall. Companies shed workers to fatten shrinking margins.</p><p> In Shanghai, Liu Wang has held off on plans to upgrade his apartment because he is worried about sinking more money into a property whose value he believes <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">could keep dropping</a> .</p><p> “The economic condition is highly uncertain now,” said Liu, who works at a logistics firm that is shifting its focus toward domestic business after its export business weakened. In his hometown of Qufu in China&#39;s northeastern Shandong province, demand for homes has been tepid despite a drop in prices, he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826215?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Electric-vehicle prices have been falling in China as sales growth slows and automakers battle for market share.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Qilai Shen/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The housing bubble is still quite large,” Liu added. “I don&#39;t see any reason why prices will go up.”</p><p> In Japan, deflation first appeared in 1995. Excluding a few respites, it more or less stuck around until the 2008-09 financial crisis. Even today, Japan is battling to sustain higher rates of price growth with ultraloose central bank policies.</p><p> One textbook response is a massive monetary expansion, lowering interest rates and printing money to spur borrowing and spending, which in theory should trigger more inflation.</p><p> But data show Chinese companies are reluctant to take on new debt to expand production, while droves of homeowners are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-consumers-lack-of-confidence-is-causing-a-rush-of-mortgage-prepayments-15691754?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">choosing to repay mortgages early</a> . Both are signs of weak demand for loans, muffling the effectiveness of interest-rate cuts.</p><p> A major reason is that many companies and households already have such large debts that they don&#39;t want to add more. Household debt has surged to 1.5 times that of income, far above the level of most developed countries, including the US, according to calculations by Jens Presthus, associate director of Global Counsel, an advisory firm.</p><p> Deflation, or even just the fear of deflation, can make the problem worse. Borrowers worry the cost of servicing their debts is going to rise, so they respond by saving more and spending less.</p><p> “Deflation is particularly dangerous when there&#39;s a lot of debt,” said Arthur Budaghyan, chief emerging markets economist at BCA Research. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826217?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese companies are reluctant to take on new debt while homeowners are choosing to repay mortgages early.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Jason Douglas at <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com</a> and Stella Yifan Xie at <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf<author><![CDATA[Jason DouglasStella Yifan Xie]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>indicators</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>经济新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Don’t Be a Jerk at Work. (But Don’t Be Too Nice, Either.)]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> How devolving into people-pleasing can hold back your career <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825131/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption><span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091056"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091056"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-736144/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig" itemprop="url" rel="author">Rachel Feintzeig</a></span> | Photo illustrations and <span class="author" itemprop="name">video by Aaron DuRall for The Wall Street Journal</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 30, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> How nice should you be at work?</p><p> We&#39;ve supposedly moved on from the era of the militaristic chief executive who barks orders and threats. Most of us agree: We <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/office-jerk-how-to-tell-9f69a49f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">don&#39;t like jerks</a> . Be kind, we implore our kids.</p><p> Then we get to the office. We&#39;ve got direct reports to rally, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/voluntold-voluntelling-work-tips-1aadced1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">colleagues in other departments</a> to convince and bosses who claim they want honest feedback. Speak with hesitation and you&#39;re ignored. Handle your team with kid gloves and you&#39;re a pushover, not a force to be reckoned with.</p><p> “I, personally, think you&#39;re too nice a person to be in the job that you&#39;re in.” That&#39;s what Rep. Greg Murphy (R., NC) told Katherine Tai, the lead trade negotiator for the US, this spring during a hearing. His comments summed up feedback so many of us, especially women, have heard. We&#39;re too bubbly or kind. We deploy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/want-power-stop-saying-sorry-so-much-11666479801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">too many apologies</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shes-not-mad-shes-just-not-using-exclamation-points-1540267501?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">exclamation marks</a> . Yet when we do too little of all that, we&#39;re overly aggressive.</p><p> “I want to be a nice person,” Sarah Kleinberg, the director of operations at a healthcare consulting firm, told me. She has realized, though, that being nice often makes others feel good, without actually moving a project forward or prompting a team member to improve.</p><p> “You have to have the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brag-at-work-without-sounding-like-a-jerk-11675008352?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">level of confidence</a> to be beyond people-pleasing,” she says.</p><h3> &#39;Customer-service voice&#39;</h3><p> Many people, desperate not to offend, resort to what speaking coach Samara Bay calls “customer-service voice.” It&#39;s that high-pitched, upspeak-y tone meant to inform the barista, <em>I think you might be out of oat milk?</em></p><p> What are we saying when we use that tone? “I&#39;m not powerful, don&#39;t worry,” Bay says.</p><p> Making yourself nonintimidating and as small as possible might work earlier in careers, she adds, making the people in charge feel secure. But as we ascend, or try to, the wavering voices can confuse others. Do it enough and people might question whether you&#39;re leadership material, Bay says. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="482" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825189?width=700&amp;height=482" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p> She recommends a vocal exercise for<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvILkq-plHW/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">speaking more confidently</a> . Pretend that you&#39;re introducing yourself—“Hi, my name is Rachel”—while throwing a pretend ball against the wall. Match your vocal pitch to the ball&#39;s trajectory. When you throw the ball down to the ground, you&#39;ll hear your voice droop in energy along with the ball. Then throw the ball up, and notice the way your words sound as if you&#39;re half taking them back. Last, throw the ball straight and allow your words to follow through, too.</p><p> “It&#39;s the weirdest feeling to say something and mean it all the way to the end,” Bay says. “It feels brave.”</p><h3> No hedging allowed</h3><p> When pitching an idea, don&#39;t undercut yourself with hedging language, says Bob Bordone, a negotiations coach. He cringes at questions like: “Would you be willing to consider letting me <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hack-your-workweek-to-leave-early-on-summer-fridays-9752ee8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">work remotely on Fridays</a> ?”</p><p> “It makes me just want to say no because it&#39;s such a weak thing,” he says.</p><p> Instead, he says, start with a statement: “I wanted to talk to you about working out a new schedule.” Assure that any agreement you come to would be good for your manager and the company.</p><p> When someone tells you no, Bordone suggests trying: “How can we tackle this, even though we see it differently?” You sound strong and assertive, but not nasty, he says.</p><p> Good news for the nice guys among us: You don&#39;t have to give up your personality to be taken seriously.</p><p> “I&#39;m, 99.9% of the time, a jovial, happy-go-lucky guy,” says Colton Schweitzer, a user-experience designer and educator in Vancouver, Wash. When he doesn&#39;t like the direction a project is going, he pushes back by asking questions and inserting the occasional joke.</p><p> “I&#39;m smiling,” he says, “Even when I&#39;m saying, &#39;Are you sure about that?&#39;”</p><p> Because he&#39;s so pleasant, his serious moments carry weight. At one job, he cheerfully took on more work when colleagues asked—until his manager asked him to pick up the slack for an underperforming employee. He gave a resolute no. His manager dropped the issue, and seemed surprised and impressed by his response, he says.</p><p> “It&#39;s like a currency,” he says of invoking a more stern style. “When I use it, it&#39;s really valuable.”</p><h3> Less yelling, more intensity</h3><p> To be tough but not jerky, set clear expectations, says Harry Kraemer, a professor of leadership at Northwestern University&#39;s Kellogg School of Management.</p><p> Before teaching, Kraemer rose to be chief executive of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BAX" class="">Baxter International</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the healthcare company where he worked for 25 years. As a new manager, he would tried to be everyone&#39;s breezy friend, shrugging it off when his team turned in a project hours past deadline. The second time it happened, he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/boss-management-yelling-workplace-cf32b09a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">devolved into yelling</a> , only to realize he hadn&#39;t made the stakes clear from the start.</p><p> “If I focus on being liked, the chance of being respected is very low,” he says.</p><p> He adopted a new leadership style of, “I&#39;m not going to surprise you.” He says the yelling just made him look out of control, but following through with consequences worked. When his team missed sales targets, he gathered them for a two-hour debrief—no smiling, his voice intense. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=8580B420-EE92-4C60-AB07-B0296746C53B" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"><span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“I don&#39;t need a sorry,” he would tell them. “Hit the number. Do what you told me you were going to do.”</p><p> Dinah Davis, a Realtor in Highlands, NC, still remembers advice an old friend gave her years ago on the golf course. The friend was a skilled neurosurgeon known for being direct, not touchy-feely.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Do you think you can be too nice at work? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> “I have a great bedside manner,” she told Davis. “I just don&#39;t have time for it.”</p><p> The advice was freeing for Davis, a former lawyer more comfortable with staunch negotiations than chirpy small talk.</p><p> “Do you want your pilot to be nice?” Davis asks. “Or do you want your pilot to get the plane on the ground?”</p><p> Write to Rachel Feintzeig at <a href="mailto:Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/abc0d988-98a3-49dd-87e2-f6d4256e8c3e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8<author><![CDATA[Rachel Feintzeig]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Baxter International</category><category> BAX </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[West African Leaders Threaten Force Against Niger Plotters]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>经济组织实施制裁，给军政府7天时间恢复民主统治<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097007"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826385?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，数千名抗议者游行至法国驻尼日尔首都尼亚美大使馆。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097007"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-hinshaw" itemprop="url" rel="author">德鲁·欣肖</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福孔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 30 日下午 3:43（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>西非领导人表示，他们将考虑进行军事干预，驱逐<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blinken-says-u-s-aid-to-niger-in-jeopardy-following-coup-766a0156?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">尼日尔的政变策划者</a>，并恢复这个幅员辽阔的撒哈拉国家的民主统治，他们担心这个国家可能成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-need-of-allies-putin-courts-african-leaders-in-st-petersburg-b6596a7b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯在该地区最新的安全伙伴</a>。</p><p>周日在尼日利亚首都阿布贾举行的紧急峰会上，西非国家经济共同体领导人表示，尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新军政府</a>有一周时间让该国民选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆重新掌权。这个名为西非经共体的区域组织还制定了银行业和经济制裁措施，以压制军政府。周三，军政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了巴祖姆</a>及其家人，并暂停了该国宪法。</p><p> “如果当局的要求在一周内得不到满足，[西非经共体]将采取一切必要措施恢复尼日尔共和国的宪法秩序，”西非经共体委员会主席奥马尔·阿留·图雷在会后表示。 “此类措施可能包括使用武力。”</p><p>当天早些时候，尼日尔首都尼亚美的数千名抗议者游行到该国前殖民统治者法国大使馆，挥舞着俄罗斯国旗，投掷石块并点火。 “法国离开”，几块人群自制的标语牌上写着。法国军队在尼日尔驻有约 1,500 名士兵，这是在尼日尔这个面积约为法国本土两倍的广阔沙漠国家进行的长达数年的打击伊斯兰叛乱分子行动的一部分。</p><p>数年的政变导致该地区其他几个国家的亲俄罗斯政府上台，数个西非国家对尼日尔进行军事干预的威胁不断升级。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwest-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Secretary of State Antony Blinken said Saturday that the military coup in Niger jeopardized US aid and security support worth hundreds of millions of dollars. The European Union also suspended security cooperation and financial support with Niger. Photo: Darren England/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>自 2020 年以来，军事领导人在马里和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/burkina-faso-soldiers-take-control-of-state-tv-declare-countercoup-11664573837?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">布基纳法索</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-mali-coup-mutineers-pledge-fresh-elections-11597825118?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">夺取了权力</a>，这两个国家曾经是法国和美国在西非最亲密的反恐伙伴，这使得这些国家的效忠转向了莫斯科。政变领导人从当地的挫败感中受益，因为西方军队曾在两国驻扎了数千名士兵，却未能击败在该地区蔓延的圣战叛乱分子。</p><p>对于尼日利亚这个非洲人口最多的国家和最大的经济体来说，尼日尔的政变走得太远了，尼日利亚与北部邻国有着 1000 英里的边界。尼日利亚对其内部伊斯兰叛乱分子的战争取决于与尼日尔的跨境协调。</p><p>华盛顿已花费超过 5 亿美元装备和训练当地军队，也面临着失去该地区合作伙伴的风险；美国法律限制向军事统治下的国家提供此类援助。自 2017 年以来，欧盟已承诺向该国提供超过 15 亿欧元（约合 17 亿美元）的援助，但欧盟可能会失去这个曾帮助减缓寻求庇护者向北前往利比亚并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-shipwreck-shakes-italys-anti-immigration-government-b35a6d81?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">继续前往该</a>国的国家的合作。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-shipwreck-shakes-italys-anti-immigration-government-b35a6d81?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">意大利</a>。周六，欧盟表示将冻结对尼日尔的部分支持。</p><p> Aside from threatening military force, the West African leaders announced banking and trade restrictions that reflected their hope that the junta around Gen. Omar Tchiani, who earlier this week declared himself Niger&#39;s new leader, doesn&#39;t have the full support of the country&#39;s military.</p><p>尼日利亚总统博拉·蒂努布的新政府</p>is hoping economic pressure, combined with the threat of force, can get the coup leaders to step down, a senior Nigerian official said.这位官员表示，他们还对俄罗斯在曾经向前殖民者法国寻求指导的国家扩大其存在深感担忧。<p></p><p> “现在这是一场大国博弈，”他说。 “这是法国和俄罗斯之间的事情。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DC3DD938-33C6-4ADA-887D-E8ED2882AEA7&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwest-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔总统卫队负责人周五在士兵发动政变推翻总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆后宣布自己为国家领导人。军队警告不要外国军事干预以恢复巴祖姆的地位。 Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>周六，军政府发言人阿马杜·阿卜杜拉马内少校出现在国家电视台上，表示他想提醒“西非国家经济共同体或任何其他冒险家，我们保卫祖国的坚定决心。”</p><p> The US and Europe have made Niger the centerpiece of their fight against the spread of Islamic State and al Qaeda in Africa&#39;s Sahel, the semiarid southern shore of the Sahara.该国拥有美国无人机和美国突击队，他们训练了尼日尔特种部队，在战斗任务中为他们提供建议，并为他们配备了从帐篷、无线电到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。</p><p>相比之下，马里在 2021 年雇佣了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-wagner-group-mercenaries-mali-west-africa-11661099199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯瓦格纳集团</a>的雇佣兵，而布基纳法索今年早些时候驱逐了法国军队。</p><p> French President Emmanuel Macron condemned the violence at his country&#39;s embassy and warned that France would respond “immediately and uncompromisingly” to any attack on its citizens, military, diplomats and diplomatic compounds.根据巴祖姆政党社交媒体账户发布的视频，政变发生后，尼亚美的其他抗议者也立即站出来支持巴祖姆。</p><p>巴黎外交部后来说，法国大使馆的安全措施已得到加强。 It added that France backs the sanctions imposed by Ecowas on Niger.</p><p>美国和欧洲官员指责俄罗斯利用虚假信息在萨赫勒地区煽动反西方情绪。</p><p>除了威胁可能进行军事干预外，以尼日利亚为首的 15 个国家集团还表示，将立即冻结政府在该地区中央银行和商业银行的银行账户。它还冻结了尼日尔与其邻国之间的所有能源相关交易。尼日尔三分之二以上的电力从尼日利亚进口。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>该国与七个西非邻国使用相同的货币，这些邻国的储备由总部位于塞内加尔达喀尔的中央银行管理。西非经共体表示，这些资产应立即冻结。</p><p>声明称，如果策划者不让巴祖姆重新掌权，欧盟还将针对策划者实施禁飞区、旅行禁令和资产冻结。这些措施与 2021 年对马里实施的措施类似，当时马里未能遵守推动该国走向民主选举的计划。</p><p> The banking sanctions will likely have limited impact on Niger, where the overwhelming majority of citizens are unbanked, and could backfire by allowing Russia to step in as a new patron for the country&#39;s coup leaders, said Bismarck Rewane, managing director of Lagos research firm Financial Derivatives.</p><p> “这会产生排斥他们的影响，但作用不大，”他说。 “这是一个很好的原声片段……最大的恐惧是它给俄罗斯人带来的恐惧。”</p><p>然而，一些非洲国家仍然希望尼日尔的对峙能够和平结束。</p><p>乍得信息部长阿齐兹·穆罕默德·萨利赫表示，乍得过渡总统穆罕默德·代比周日在尼亚美会见了尼日尔军政府领导人之一萨利福·莫迪，试图解决危机。乍得官员表示，这次访问是在与尼日利亚协商之后进行的。</p><p>巴祖姆拒绝下台或离开他的住所，他已被政变策划者扣为人质五天。 “他很平静，并表示无意辞职，”巴祖姆领导的尼日尔民主与社会主义党领导人安吉·巴鲁·切卡劳 (Ange Barou Chekaraou) 表示，他曾通过电话与他交谈。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Gbenga Akingbule 和 Noemie Bisserbe 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Drew Hinshaw ( <a href="mailto:drew.hinshaw@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">drew.hinshaw@wsj.com)</a>和 Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 19:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7<author><![CDATA[Drew HinshawBenoit Faucon]]></author><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Political/General News</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Rebellion</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>International Sanctions</category><category> Politics/International Relations</category><category> Domestic Politics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>political</category><category> general news</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>armed rebellion</category><category> armed forces</category><category> international relations</category><category> international sanctions</category><category>政治</category><category>domestic politics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>restrictions</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bombing in Pakistan Kills at Least 40]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在今年大选前对目标宗教政党进行爆炸<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097073"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=11FC4A49-0C81-4828-8FEB-D913936FD93B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">周日，一名炸弹袭击者对巴基斯坦西北部的一个政治集会发动袭击，造成数十人死亡。照片：法亚兹·阿齐兹/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097073"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/saeed-shah" itemprop="url" rel="author">赛义德·沙阿</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">萨夫达尔·达瓦尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 30 日下午 3:17（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>巴基斯坦伊斯兰堡——官员称，周日，一个政党集会发生的爆炸事件造成至少 40 人死亡，巴基斯坦在今年大选前面临新一波的恐怖主义浪潮。</p><p>这次爆炸袭击的目标是一个宗教政党，毛拉纳·法兹鲁尔·拉赫曼领导的伊斯兰促进会，该党宣扬强硬的伊斯兰教，但对于认为民主非伊斯兰的圣战分子来说还不够极端。没有人立即声称对此事负责。</p><p>当地的视频片段显示，党的支持者聚集在为会议搭建的大帐篷里，聆听党内一些高级领导人的讲话，火球猛然喷发。视频显示，随后，血淋淋的尸体和被肢解的尸体散落在地上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826401?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">人们正在调查巴基斯坦西北部靠近阿富汗边境的致命爆炸现场。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: hanifullah khan/epa/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>警方表示，这起袭击发生在该国西北部靠近阿富汗边境的地区，是一名自杀式炸弹袭击者，并补充说，由于许多伤者情况危急，死亡人数可能会上升。一些伤势最重的人被军用直升机送往省会白沙瓦的一家医院。省政府称，除40多人死亡外，还有200人受伤。</p><p>总理谢赫巴兹·谢里夫表示：“从这次袭击中可以清楚地看出，敌人正在反对巴基斯坦的民主制度。” “我们永远不会让这种懦弱的攻击的目的得逞。”</p><p>受到攻击的政党是谢里夫领导的联合政府的一部分。根据宪法规定，选举最迟将于 11 月上旬举行。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323741004578416232504368610?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2013年，巴基斯坦经历了一场血腥选举</a>，当时恐怖主义的威胁要大得多。随后，随着巴基斯坦境内军事行动的开展，袭击事件逐渐减少，直到 2021 年塔利班接管阿富汗为止。</p><p>伊斯兰堡称，驻扎在阿富汗的武装分子<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistani-militants-test-taliban-promise-not-to-host-terror-groups-11651150686?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在巴基斯坦发动袭击</a>。阿富汗塔利班政府否认那里有巴基斯坦武装分子。</p><p>喀布尔塔利班政府谴责这起爆炸事件，并补充说“这种令人发指的行为在任何宗教或教派中都是不正当的”。</p><p>周日的爆炸是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-bombing-at-police-compound-kills-at-least-28-11675086228?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">自一月份一座清真寺遭到袭击</a>以来最致命的一次。同样在该国西北部，爆炸造成约 80 人死亡，其中大部分是在那里做礼拜的警察。</p><p>巴基斯坦塔利班是一个受阿富汗组织启发的圣战运动，是大多数袭击事件的幕后黑手。巴基斯坦军方在 2021 年和 2022 年与该组织举行了不成功的和谈，但这使得一些武装分子得以返回巴基斯坦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826410?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日爆炸中的一名受伤受害者被送往白沙瓦的一家医院。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：穆罕默德·萨贾德/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>同样活跃的还有伊斯兰国激进组织的当地分支，该组织在巴基斯坦和阿富汗都有活动。</p><p>新加坡拉惹勒南国际研究学院高级副研究员阿卜杜勒·巴西特表示，这次袭击具有伊斯兰国的特征，该组织此前曾针对巴基斯坦的宗教政党进行过袭击。他说，巴基斯坦塔利班现在的重点是袭击军事和警察人员。</p><p> “巴基斯坦没有好的选择来应对这一威胁，”巴斯特说。 “国内没有大规模反恐行动的公众支持或资金。他们在阿富汗进行的任何空袭和秘密暗杀都会造成更多问题。”</p><p>喀布尔的塔利班政府坚称，它不会允许该国领土被用来对付其他国家，并对巴基斯坦和其他邻国任何侵犯其领土的行为做出强烈反应。</p><p>写信给 Saeed Shah，邮箱为<a href="mailto:saeed.shah@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">saeed.shah@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 19:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839<author><![CDATA[Saeed Shah]]></author><category> Political/General News</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Crime/Legal Action</category><category> Politics/International Relations</category><category> Domestic Politics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Terrorism</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>crime</category><category> legal action</category><category>政治</category><category>international relations</category><category> domestic politics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>terrorism</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e executive news filter</category></item></channel></rss>